✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: C'est original !

Hello,
As StepBack13 mentionned already, I'd remove the k & M, as I think it would require too much for a clash in addition to formula parsing.
Really nice contribution though.
Quite interesting problem, but too hard for a clash I think. The simplest way to solve this I could put forward still includes knowledge about parsing.

Nice clash idea, but maybe a bit too hard? I couldn't solve it in 5 minutes. Took me about 10 as someone who knows these formulas already. I also used RegEx and recursion, which meant I could solve it in about 6 lines of code. I think that most clashers would struggle even harder on this one, but I do like it a lot. :)

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Interesting Clash.

Goal
* Paragraph 1: Please format all instances of "+" and "|" as {{constants}}.

* Please delete the example. An example has already been shown in Example section.

Input
* Suggest to delete "as a mathematical formula".

* Please format "k" and "M" as {{constants}}.

* Please delete the example. An example has already been shown in Example section.

Solution code
* I haven't checked your code in detail, but it seems that you perform a rounding every time when you call the `calculate_parallel` function. It can give a different result if the rounding is peformed only once at the end.

Luckily that doesn't seem to affect the output for your cases, but I've tried this case:
1M + (7k | 11k) + 100 + (17k | 13k)
The result is 1011745 if I use your code but 1011744 if I round the result at the end only.

The statement should clearly specify **When** rounding should be performed. Rounding at the end only (i.e. no rounding in any intermediate calculation steps) makes more sense to me.

Output
* What do you mean by "rounding up or down depends on the descendants"? Please be clear. I think writing "Total resistance rounded to the nearest integer" is sufficient.

Constraints
* Please format "+" and "|" as {{constants}}.

* Please add: "All individual values in [[formula]] are positive integers."

Thanks.
Thank you for your detailed feedback. It was very helpful and I fixed everything you mentioned. :)
One idea to make it easier would be to remove the "M"s and "k"s and just use integers everywhere? This would certainly make it easier for most clashers to solve.
